paragraphs.p:
Consider the pair of equations
      \begin{split}
      \color{seq-red}x - 3y &\color{seq-red}{}= -3 \\
      \color{seq-blue} 2x + y &\color{seq-blue}{}= 8\color{black}.
      \end{split}

      The solution set of these equations is the set of all pairs (x,y) that make both of the equations true.  Each equation defines a line in \R^2, so the solution set of the system of equations is the unique point where the two lines intersect.

